Class MagicSquare

  • java.lang.Object
    • MagicSquare

  • public class MagicSquare
extends java.lang.Object
    MagicSquare class builds a MagicSquare and contains all of the methods that are necessary to check if the given square is actually a MagicSquare. It does this using methods that check the sums of the diagonals, the rows, and the columns. A proper MagicSquare will have the exact same sum in each column, row, and diagonal.

    • Method Detail

      • isMagic

        public boolean isMagic()
        isMagic method checks if the square is a proper MagicSquare using loops to check if the rows, columns, and diagonals sum up to the same value. It accomplishes this using for loops to check each sum against every other sum by storing each sum in an array and then checking that the values in each array are the same value.
        Returns:
        a boolean that is true if the constraints of a MagicSquare are met and false if one of the properties fails

      • isUnique

        private boolean isUnique(java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.Integer> numbers)
        isUnique checks if the given list of numbers contains any duplicate values. This is done by using a HashSet and checking if the HashSet size is smaller than the size of the list (which would mean there are duplicates in the list)
        Parameters:
        numbers - the ArrayList of user input integers
        Returns:
        true if there are no duplicates and false if there are duplicates

      • isSquare

        private boolean isSquare(java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.Integer> numbers)
        isSquare checks if the ArrayList of user input integers is a square. It accomplishes this by taking the square root of the size and making sure that, when squared, that root equals the size of the ArrayList.
        Parameters:
        numbers - the ArrayList of user input integers
        Returns:
        returns whether the root multiplied by the root is equal to the size of the ArrayList, and thus, that the given inputs can create a square
